String subSystemsIntroOne =
    'At the inception of the University of Lagos in 1962 only three Engineering programmes were established in the Faculty of Engineering. These were: Civil Engineering, Electrical Engineering and Mechanical Engineering. As teaching and research grew and diverse needs of intra-collaboration began to surface among academics and teaching units, there arose the necessity of establishment of a unit which would spearhead analytical discuss and assist researchers in their analytical needs. As a result, a unit called Engineering Analysis Unit was established under Civil Engineering Department for this purpose. The foundation team of Engineering Analysts academicians in the Unit included late Professor K. A. Aderogba, a renown Mathematics with heavy bias towards Applied Mathematics and late Professor E. E. Okon an Electrical Engineer of repute. Later, late Professor Vincent Olusegun Sowemimo Olunloyo, Cornel trained Mechanical Engineer and late Professor Oyewusi Ibidapo-Obe an Applied Mathematician in Civil Engineering from University of Waterloo joined. Initially, the Unit was purely a Research and Collaboration unit with no mandate to teach any independent course in the faculty. Then came 1983. The Engineering Analysis Unit under Civil Engineering was granted autonomy to operate as an academic unit on its own with the extra mandate to teach all Engineering Mathematics courses in the faculty.';
String subSystemsIntroTwo =
    'Bye and bye, the Unit was also granted Senate approval to run Masters of Science, Master of Philosophy and Doctor of Philosophy programmes in Engineering Analysis even though there was no undergraduate programme on ground at that time in the Unit. Four out of the Professors currently in the Department of Systems Engineering and over two hundred others are products of the M.Sc./M.Phil./Ph.D. programmes which started in Engineering Analysis Unit.   Then came the era of deployment of cybernetic and artificial Intelligence tools in analysis and research. Engineering Analysis Unit fully identified with the development and coupled with the growing need for an engineering programme that will take up and provide graduates for the contemporary ever complex and multi-disciplinary nature of modern engineering problems and projects, the necessity of establishment of Systems Engineering programme was conceived. Therefore, in the October year 2000, approval of the Senate of the University of Lagos was obtained for the establishment of the Department of Systems Engineering from the Engineering Analysis Unit to run Bachelor of Science degree course in Systems Engineering as well as keep the original mandate of teaching all Engineering Mathematics courses in the Faculty given to the defunct Engineering Analysis Unit. The Bachelor’s degree in Systems Engineering started with focused specializations of Engineering Analysis, encapsulating the entirety of the programmes of the defunct Engineering Analysis Unit, Robotics and Artificial Intelligence, Control Engineering and Simulation and Modeling in a bid to establish programme components running in rhythm with contemporary needs and technological focus. In 2003, the new department as an attestation to the solid background in staffing and resources was granted Senate approval to run postgraduate programmes leading to the award of Master of Science, Master of Philosophy and Doctor of Philosophy in Systems Engineering. The B.Sc. Systems Engineering curriculum has been kept dynamic over the years in response to the equally dynamic technological needs and advancement of contemporary academic, societal and global environment. Hence, from the initial very bold step taken by the founders of floating a robust, state of the art programme in response to the need to meet the complexity and multi-disciplinary needs of contemporary engineering problems, the curriculum has gone through a couple of reviews sequel to the adoption of the current Core Curriculum Minimum Academic Standard (CCMAS) and Outcome-Based Education approach. In the current CCMAS curriculum of the department, specialties have been comprehensively reviewed, again in response to contemporary needs and technological developments, to a 5-unit specialization structure in which each unit headed by a Professor has the potential of metamorphosing into a virile academic teaching unit. The specialties are (1) Multi-Physical Systems (2) Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning Systems (3) Industrial Systems (4) Electronics and Control Systems and (5) Bio-Inspired and Energy Systems. The incipient adoption of Outcome-Based Education approach has also revolutionized our B.Eng. (Systems Engineering) programme as we focus on our graduate outputs meeting the programmes set objectives and tuning teaching and learning to be in consonance.';
String pOE = 'Programme Educational Objective (PEO)';
String pOESub =
    'Key Programme Educational Objectives (PEOs) of the Bachelor of Engineering programme in Systems Engineering were articulated to vent and support the actualization of the programme’s vision and mission in line with those of the University of Lagos. They are bases of checkmating the operations of the programme and clear indicators to monitor quality and track the execution of the programme in line with our vision and mission. The PEOs are scheduled to be reviewed every 5 years alongside the curriculum to keep the program afloat of global technological thrusts, relevance to our immediate environment and national needs and employability in the contemporary market especially in terms of relevance to the industry. The Bachelor of Engineering in Systems Engineering programme is expected to meet the following objectives in producing graduates.';
